Chris Webber, who would not talk about allegations he received financial aid from a booster before turning pro, had 28 points, eight assists, seven rebounds and two
blocks as the Sacramento Kings beat the Detroit Pistons 107-86 Wednesday night.

article.headline: Webber shakes off allegations, shakes up Pistons

article.linkText: Central-leading Pistons no match for Kings, Webber
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Chris Webber's plan worked out perfectly. Before the game, Webber didn't want to talk about allegations that he received a lot of money from a booster before turning pro -- and he didn't. He wanted to dominate during it -- and he did. Webber had 28 points, eight assists, seven rebounds and two blocks as the Sacramento Kings beat the Detroit Pistons 107-86 Wednesday night. "I didn't play with anger," Webber said. "I played with focus." Webber has been the focus of numerous questions and commentary since a federal indictment was released two weeks ago that alleged he received $280,000 from an ex-Michigan booster, while he was a Detroit Country Day and Michigan star. Most fans booed and berated Webber -- in part because he didn't sign with Detroit as a free agent last summer -- and that only seemed to motivate him even more. "Jon Barry told me, 'I wish they hadn't gotten you upset,' because he was with me for three years," Webber said. "I had some extra incentive to play for. The worst thing you can do is wake a sleeping giant. Not that I'm all that great, but when my back is to the wall, I do come out fighting." The Kings maintained the best record in the NBA by winning their sixth straight and ninth in 10 games. They set a franchise record with their sixth consecutive road victory, and matched franchise marks for wins (55) and road victories (22). Mike Bibby and Vlade Divac complemented Webber's night with 15 points each. The Central Division-leading Pistons had won nine of 11. Corliss Williamson scored 13, Jerry Stackhouse had 12, and Ben Wallace added 12 points, 11 rebounds and two blocks. "We needed to have our 'A-game,' and we just didn't have it," Detroit coach Rick Carlisle said. "They are really good, so it added up to a humbling experience." Webber wasted little time showing the skills -- and the menacing snarl -- that he began to display over 10 years ago to many of the people who came to see him play Wednesday night. Within the first 31 seconds of the game, he made a mid-range jumper, a dunk followed by a loud slap on the backboard, and waved his hand and shouted at some of the fans heckling him. When he wasn't making one of his first nine shots, he was tossing no-look and around-the-back passes or snatching rebounds. "He's always more focused when he comes back here," Barry said. "With all the commotion, I'm sure he was pumped up even more. He had a tremendous game." Webber helped Sacramento, which never trailed, seize control of the game with eight points, three assists, two rebounds and a block as it led 37-16 after one quarter. The Kings led by as many as 29 points in the second quarter, and were ahead 62-43 at halftime. Detroit didn't get closer than 17 points in the third, and 20 in the final quarter. When Webber was taken out of the game for the first time with 4:34 left, he had missed just four of his 16 shots and had done little to encourage a crowd that was mostly against him. He said, "this is my house," to himself just before the start, and he shouted that at some fans during the game. "You can't trade me from Detroit, I live here," he said. "A lot of people play for the team, but I play for the city wherever I go. I'm a Detroiter, and I was just proud to tell that to a couple people tonight. ... I'm going to have front-row seats here when I retire." Within the next two weeks, Webber said he plans to discuss the federal indictment alleging that former booster Ed Martin lent Webber about $280,000 from 1988-93, a period extending from his freshman year in high school through his sophomore season in college. "I am anxious to give answers to all of these questions, but I've been advised to wait to do that," Webber said. "I think people that know me know that I'm not one to leave things unanswered. I've always been the first one to stand up and take responsibility. I definitely want to get this thing over, but right now we're in the midst of a championship run, hopefully." Game notes
Former Michigan State star Mateen Cleaves, who was traded to Sacramento for Barry and a future No. 1 pick last summer, played in the final minutes and had two points and three assists. ... Barry scored seven points. ... Sacramento's Peja Stojakovic, who hasn't played since March 19, missed the game with a strained right hamstring. ... Detroit is 1-6 against the top four teams in the Western Conference. ... Detroit rookie Rodney White played in a first half for the first time since December.
